<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Linseed Oil" class="currentChild" href="Linseed_Oil">Linseed Oil</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
A natural oil obtained from the seeds of the flax plant (any of several plants of the genus <em>Linum</em>, especially <em>L. usitatissimum'), used as the basis of <a title="Drying Oil Vehicle" href="Drying_Oil_Vehicle">drying oil vehicle</a>s and <a title="Varnish" href="Varnish">varnish</a>es in the production of printing inks. Linseed oil that has been refined by exposure to high temperatures is called <a title="Stand Oil" href="Stand_Oil">stand oil</a>, a term which is also used in the United Kingdom to refer to linseed oil in general. Soaps or fatty acids of linseed oil are called <a title="linoleates" class="nonexistent" href="http://printwiki.org/linoleates">linoleates</a> and are frequently used in the manufacture of printing ink <a title="Drier" href="Drier">drier</a>s. 
</p>
